<text><front></front><body>
<dateline>APRIL, 1844.</dateline><lb/><pb n="212" facs="#f0001" />
<div n="1"><head><hi rendition="#i">Note by M. Humboldt. &#x2014;</hi></head><p>The largest piece of platina found up to<lb/>this time at Nijni Tageulsg weighs 20 lbs. (Russian), 34 zolotniks.<lb/>Piece of gold found at Miask, 10 kil. &#x00B7; 119 = 27.002 lbs. Piece of gold<lb/>found in the United States, Anson County, N. C. 21&#x00B7;70 kil. = 57&#x00B7;939 lbs.<lb/>Piece found at Rio Hayna, (1502,) and lost in the depths of the sea,<lb/>(see my critical examination of the geography of the new continent,)<lb/>14&#x00B7;500 kil. = 38&#x00B7;715 lbs. Wonderful mass of Miask found 1842, 36&#x00B7;020<lb/>kil. = 100&#x00B7;077 lbs.</p><lb/><p>According to a letter from Count Cancrine, Dec. 3, 1842, Siberia to<lb/>the east of the Ural produced in 1842 the quantity of 479 pouds of<lb/>gold = 7&#x00B7;846 kilogrammes = 21,058 pounds, and the whole of Russia<lb/>about 970 pouds = 15&#x00B7;889 kilogrammes = 42,323&#x00B7;63 pounds.</p></div><lb/></body><back></back>

